{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17626087","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17626087"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:34:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:34:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17058"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17058","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17058"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.15,0.79,0,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9748"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77022"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9748","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9748"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17058"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62528"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5300"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22926"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23116"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77022","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77022"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents with recurrent episodes of severe joint pain affecting his great toe. His serum urate is 0.54 mmol/L (0.23-0.42). He is prescribed a xanthine oxidase inhibitor.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of xanthine oxidase inhibitors?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Blocks reabsorption of uric acid in kidneys","Inhibits synthesis of purines","Prevents conversion of hypoxanthine to uric acid","Dissolves existing uric acid crystals","Increases urinary excretion of uric acid"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EXanthine oxidase inhibitors work by \u003Cstrong\u003Epreventing the conversion of hypoxanthine to uric acid\u003C/strong\u003E. By inhibiting this enzyme, they reduce the production of uric acid, which is the primary goal in treating conditions like gout.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks reabsorption of uric acid in kidneys\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of action of uricosuric drugs like probenecid, which work through a different pathway.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits synthesis of purines\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as these medications do not affect purine synthesis, only their downstream metabolism to uric acid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDissolves existing uric acid crystals\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect; these medications prevent new crystal formation but do not have any direct effect on existing crystals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases urinary excretion of uric acid\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect; while uric acid levels decrease with treatment, this occurs through reduced production rather than increased excretion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy preventing uric acid formation, xanthine oxidase inhibitors help reduce uric acid levels in the blood and tissues, thereby preventing gout attacks and kidney stone formation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Xanthine oxidase converts hypoxanthine to xanthine and then to uric acid in purine metabolism.","Xanthine oxidase inhibitors like allopurinol work by preventing the formation of uric acid.","Xanthine oxidase inhibitors are primarily used to treat gout and prevent uric acid kidney stones."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62528"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17058"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62528","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62528"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T22:33:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T22:35:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9748"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77022"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving 